<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-106-938  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 106 938.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  April 1989 v62 n4 p119(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Concurrent is sitting pretty after an unconventional buyout.andO;(Concurrent Computer Corp. will pay no taxes for three to fiveyears as a result of its leveraged buyout by MassachusettsComputer Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Shandle, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The complex Oct 1988 leveraged buyout of Concurrent Computer Corp(Tinton Falls, NJ) by smaller Massachusetts Computer Corp(Masscomp, Westford, MA) resulted in significant tax savings forthe combined firm (named Concurrent) which, at $400 million sales,is the largest firm dedicated solely to standards-based real-timecomputing.andP;  Concurrent facilitated the $247 Masscomp buyout bycontributing $77 million cash and raising the remaining $170million from venture capital firms and through a junk-bond issue.andO;Complexities in the tax laws allowed double entry of several majorbuyout expenses, all of which can be depreciated on the corporateincome-tax return.andP;  The combined company addresses the entireprice/performance range of real-time computing with productsranging from software and real-time UNIX operating systems to $1million parallel-processing computer systems.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Concurrent Computer Corp. (acquisitions and mergers)Massachusetts Computer Corp. (acquisitions and mergers).andO;Ticker:    CCUR.andO;Topic:     MergerAcquisitionImpact AnalysisTaxReal-Time SystemsManufacturersComputer industryFinancial Analysis.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Concurrent and Masscomp profit or loss: 1984-88. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>